segments.text: Okay, now if I'm you, give us your opinion of the protest movement, the people involved with them, and any legacies that may have resulted from these movements and these people.
All right.
Several changes were brought about as a result of the protests.
Changes in housing, changes in university regulations.
I cannot detail any of those from memory, but there's more openness in admissions for all students and efforts to attract minority students.
The university, from where I've observed it,
They've spent time and money and effort to try to get a better mix in the enrollment, and of course then they've struggled with the problem of enrollment keeping on climbing.
It was 24,564 when I went there, and it's now more than 50,000 students.
they would like to get them down below that, but they can't do it.

The president making a speech at the retired faculty staff meeting a few years ago in which I was in attendance said that the regents are wanting to limit enrollment, they're wanting to lower the enrollment, but the very people that
that furnish the support for the university are people that want their kids and their friends' kids to keep getting into the university.
So it's a sort of a vicious circle or cycle.
They have to fight on the basis of that.
But thinking about the climate, the educational climate, the racial climate,
The economic climate that existed in 64 and on into the 70s and a little bit into the 80s, I guess, it was just right and right for protests for change, for a call for change.
And I think that some of the things that the, and I'll use the word, dissident students,
some of the students that were unhappy with the military and governmental and collegiate complex.
There were some things that needed to be looked at the total picture and make some changes.
And I think that the university wouldn't have made some of the changes to it if there hadn't
a catalyst that pushing and that the students hadn't gained enough ground for their voices to be heard.
And student government at the university has always been a pretty activist group, but it never was as active as during the years that
that the SDS had a good bit to say.
I would have to leave it to the chroniclers of the period writing for the university, and Dr. Margaret Berry is the person that's done more in writing and preserving the history
of the University of Texas, and she would be a fine person for you to contact and ask for any comments she may have or information she may have that would help to strengthen this.
But I think that it would be ludicrous to say that the movement
wasn't positive.
It had some negative elements involved in it, but it was for some good causes and changed the need to be made.
And of course, in an organization the size of the university, it takes a pretty active, noisy minority to get things done.
And this was the catalyst and the nucleus around which a lot of students and I have been asked about the percentage, and I don't know.
I have to say that there was not mass demonstrating on the campus.
There was masses there a time or two demonstrating for Cambodia and for
Kent State, but the others were just chipping away and getting the attention of the university administration.
I think when the period is written up and remembered by the historians, it won't be a dark period on the campus of the university.
It will be a light period.
where some changes were made that ought to be made for an enlightened community such as UT.
So from my perspective and point of view and position as a staff member there, I think the protest was a necessary thing.
